		                     		  <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
		  <ol>		    
		    <li> (For me) Learn what causes seasons.</li>
		    <li>Learn the radial solutions for the Schrodinger equation corresponding to the Hydrogen atom. </li>
		    <li>Learn to interpret radial probabilities for the Hydrogen atom. </li></ol>
		    <h2>What causes seasons?</h2>
		    Let us see what	    <a href="https://spaceplace.nasa.gov/seasons/en/" target= "_blank"  style="color:blue;">   NASA says.</a>
		    <h2>Angular probabilities: Blackboard clarification</h2>
		    			<center> <img src="{% static "img/angular_prob2_0.png" %}" width="470"></center>
		    			<center> <img src="{% static "img/Atomic_orbitals_3D.png" %}" width="570"></center><br><br>

	                    <h2>Schrodinger Equation(s) for Hydrogen atom </h2>
                    By writing the Schrodinger equation for a system with a central potential in Spherical coordinates, and use separation of variables we get a system of three independent differential equations, one per spherical coordinate:
                    <br><br>
                    &#x2713; The polar equation:
                    $$ {\rm sin}(\theta){\partial\over \partial\theta}\left({\rm sin}(\theta){\partial\over\partial\theta}\right)\Theta(\theta)  -C\,{\rm sin}^2(\theta)=D\Theta(\theta)$$
                    <hr>
                    &#x2713; The azimuthal equation:
                    $$ {\partial^2\Phi(\phi)\over \partial\phi^2}=-D\Phi(\phi)$$
                    <hr>
                    The radial equation:
                    $$-{\partial\over \partial r}\left(r^2{\partial\over \partial r}\right)R(r)-{2mr^2\over \hbar^2}(E-U(r))R(r)=C\,R(r)$$
                    <hr>
                    With potential energy given by,
                    \begin{equation}
                    U(r)=-{1\over4\pi \epsilon_0}{e^2\over r}\,
                    \end{equation}
                    <h3>The Radial equation</h3>
                    Now we consider the actual equation that tell apart the Hydrogen atom from any other atom, or more generally, central potential. 
                    $$-{\hbar^2\over 2 m}{1\over r^2}{\partial\over \partial r}\left(r^2{\partial\over \partial r}\right)R(r)+{ \hbar^2 \ell(\ell+1)\over 2mr^2}R(r)+U(r)R(r)=E\,R(r)\,.$$<br>
		    Observe that the angular equations does not involve energy $E$, therefore all energies involved are accounted for in the radial equation: 

                    $$ E_{\rm kinetic}\qquad+\qquad \left(E_{\rm rotational}={L^2\over 2m}\right)+\quad E_{\rm potential}=E_{\rm total} $$
		    <br><br>
                    Remember that $E$ is a conserved quantity in an isolated system. As we have mentioned before, we expect the Energies to be quantized, and they are indeed,  
                    \begin{equation}
                    E=-{m e^2\over2 (4\pi\epsilon_0)^2 n^2}={-13.6 eV\over n^2} 
                    \end{equation}
                    The quantum number $\ell$ has an important modification:
                    $$ \boxed{|L|=\hbar\sqrt{\ell(\ell+1)},\quad \ell=0,1,2,\cdots,n-1}\,. $$
                    The explanation for the last restriction comes from the fact that rotational energy can't be larger than the total energy. The quantum number $n=$ for the Hydrogen atom is known as the <b>principal quantum number</b>. 
                    <br><br>
                    By doing some algebra we can transform the radial equation into,
                    $$x Z''(x) +(2(\ell+1) -x)Z'(x)+(\lambda-(\ell+1))Z(x)=0 $$
                    where $x=\sqrt{8 m E\over \hbar^2}r,\quad\lambda={ e^2\over \hbar}\sqrt{m\over 2 E}$ and derivatives are taken with respect to $x$.
                    This equation is known as the
                    <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laguerre_polynomials" target = "_blank" style="color:blue;">associated Laguerre equation</a>, which defined the associated Laguerre polynomials.<br><br>
                    <br>
                                    <center>   <img src="{% static "img/radial_solutions.png" %}" width="500"></center><br>
                                    <h3>Degeneracy</h3>
                                    I have claim previously that degeneracy is a reflection of symmetry. The hydrogen atom being spherically symmetric, should exhibit some degree of degeneracy.<br>
				    We can quickly see that for each energy, i.e, each value of $n$, there corresponds many $\ell$'s and $m_{\ell}$'s, and since each triplet $(n,\ell,m_{\ell})$ defines a unique wavefunction $\Psi_{(n,\ell,m_{\ell})}=R_{n,\ell}\Theta_{\ell, m_{\ell}}\Phi_{m_{\ell}}$, all energy levels (except the ground state), are degenerate <br><br>
				    
Consider an electron at the energy level $n=2$, therefore $\ell$ can be $\ell_0=0,\,\ell_1=1$, but for each $\ell$, $m_{\ell}$ need to satisfy $-\ell\leq m_{\ell}\leq \ell$. What is the degree of degeneracy of such electron? i.e, how many wavefunctions/states will be at the same energy level?
				    
			<ol  style="line-height:300%" type="A">
		   <img src="{% static "img/iclicker.png" %}" width="100"> <br>
		 <!-- longer -->
		   <li>1</li>
		   <li>2</li>
		   <li>3</li>
		    <li>4</li>
		  
		 <li> None of the above </li>
			</ol>
			<br>
			What about $n=4$? What is the degree of degeneracy in such case?
			 
Consider an electron at the energy level $n=2$, therefore $\ell$ can be $\ell_0=0,\,\ell_1=1$, but for each $\ell$, $m_{\ell}$ need to satisfy $-\ell\leq m_{\ell}\leq \ell$. What is the degree of degeneracy of such electron? i.e, how many wavefunctions/states will be at the same energy level?
				    
			<ol  style="line-height:300%" type="A">
		   <img src="{% static "img/iclicker.png" %}" width="100"> <br>
		 <!-- longer -->
		   <li>4</li>
		   <li>6</li>
		   <li>9</li>
		    <li>12</li>
		  
		 <li> None of the above </li>
				</ol><br><br>
                        <center>   <img src="{% static "img/hydrogen_degen0.png" %}" width="700"></center>
			<br><br>
			Assuming that the pattern observed in the table above keep applying for higher $n$, what would you conclude?: Given a energy level $n$, the degree of degeneracy is given by,
			 	    
			<ol  style="line-height:300%" type="A">
		   <img src="{% static "img/iclicker.png" %}" width="100"> <br>
		 <!-- longer -->
		   <li>$\sqrt{n}$</li>
		   <li>$n$</li>
		   <li>$n^2$</li>
		    <li>$n^3$</li>
		  
		 <li> None of the above </li>
				</ol><br><br>
			Is easy to prove that the degeneracy at level $n$ is equal to $n^2$. <br><br>
			Before looking into the radial probabilities derived from the solutions to the radial equation, it is convenient to introduce the  <b>spectroscopic notation</b>.<br>
			
			For historical reasons, the <b>spectroscopic notation</b> is used when we talk about atoms. The notation is $(n\,\ell)$ with $\ell$ replaced by the following letters:
                                    <center>   <img src="{% static "img/spect0.png" %}" width="600"></center>
                                    The historical meaning of this letters were sharp, principal, diffuse, fundamental, g, h, i, j, k,...<br><br>
				    Example $3d$ means $n=3$ $\ell=d=2$. <br><br>
				    <b>fill in the blank</b>  Is the state $2d$ possible? _______ (yes, no).<br> 
                                    <h3>Normalization</h3>
                                    $$|\Psi_{(n,\ell,m_{\ell})}|^2=|R_{n,\ell}|^2|\Theta_{\ell, m_{\ell}}|^2 $$
                                    which is usually split into angular and radial normalizations:
                                    $$\int_{0}^{\infty}R^2(r)r^2 dr=1,\qquad 2\pi\int_0^{2\pi}\Theta^2(\theta) {\rm sin\theta}d\theta=1 $$ 
                                    <h3>Radial probabilities</h3>

                                    From the total probability expresion above, we infer that the probability per unit lenght is given by,
                                    $$ \boxed{P(r)=r^2 R^2(r)} $$
                                    plotting this function for few different energies looks like:<br><br>
                                    <center>   <img src="{% static "img/radial_prob0.png" %}" width="700"> </center>
                                    <br><br><br>
Which statement is correct?
				    		    
			<ol  style="line-height:300%" type="A">
		   <img src="{% static "img/iclicker.png" %}" width="100"> <br>
		 <!-- longer -->
		   <li> Higher $n$ has fewer nodes (regions of zero probability) </li>
		   <li> Higher $n$ has average $r$ bigger</li>
		    <li> Higher $n$ has more probability to be near to the nucleus </li>

		 <li> None of the above </li>
				</ol>
<br>
